## {{ rule.title }}

[26 U.S.C. § 24](https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/26/24) provides two related credits for dependents on the 2025 return, computed together on [Schedule 8812](https://www.irs.gov/forms-pubs/about-schedule-8812-form-1040):

- [**§ 24(a)** Child Tax Credit](https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/26/24): **$2,200** per qualifying child under age 17 (defined in [§ 152(c)](https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/26/152)) who has a valid SSN issued before the return due date ([§ 24(h)(7)](https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/26/24)). The $2,200 figure is § 24(a)'s base as substituted by post-OBBBA § 24(h)(2) for 2025; confirmed against IRS Schedule 8812 (2025) instructions and the IRS Child Tax Credit landing page. Up to **$1,700** per qualifying child is refundable as the Additional Child Tax Credit under [§ 24(d)(1)(A)](https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/26/24) (inflation-indexed via § 24(h)(5); Rev. Proc. 2024-40 § 3.05).
- [**§ 24(h)(4)** Credit for Other Dependents](https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/26/24): **$500** per qualifying child age 17+ (or qualifying relative under [§ 152(d)](https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/26/152)) with a TIN. **NON-refundable.** Children with an ITIN instead of an SSN fail § 24(h)(7) for CTC but route here.

Both credits share the [**§ 24(b)(2)** phase-out](https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/26/24): the combined credit is reduced by **$50 per $1,000** (or fraction thereof, per § 24(b)(3)) of modified AGI above **$200,000** (single / HoH / MFS) or **$400,000** (MFJ). Modified AGI for § 24 includes the [§ 911](https://uscode.house.gov/view.xhtml?req=granuleid:USC-prelim-title26-section911) excluded foreign earned income, mirroring the § 1411 NIIT add-back.

For a U.S.-citizen-in-Germany filer, [§ 152(c)(1)(B)](https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/26/152) treats months living abroad with the U.S.-citizen parent as months "with the taxpayer" — the loader does NOT require physical U.S. presence to qualify a child.

